In Week 25, the story of Trump\'92s second term turned on the fusion of power: a presidency claiming near\uc0\u8209 impunity, a Supreme Court that increasingly enabled that claim, and a civil service and enforcement apparatus being reshaped to serve it. The week\'92s events did not unfold as isolated shocks but as a pattern in which law, bureaucracy, and force were bent toward the same end. Immigration policy became a stage for fear and spectacle, disaster response a casualty of political control, and economic tools a means of punishing enemies at home and abroad. In this setting, the Democracy Clock moved from 7:49 p.m. to 7:52 p.m., a 3.5\u8209 minute slide that captured not a single coup\u8209 like moment, but a dense run of structural blows to accountability, equal citizenship, and the state\'92s capacity to serve the public rather than the regime.\
\
The previous week had left the clock at 7:49 p.m., already well into the evening of democratic risk. By the close of Week 25 it stood at 7:52 p.m., a modest shift in appearance but a sharp one in substance. The movement reflected three converging arcs. First, the Supreme Court\'92s decisions on presidential immunity and mass federal layoffs, combined with limits on nationwide injunctions, shifted the judiciary from intermittent check to active facilitator of executive projects. Second, the administration\'92s use of immigration, disaster management, and emergency powers showed law functioning less as a limit than as a weapon, applied harshly to the vulnerable and flexibly to the powerful. Third, Congress and the bureaucracy were hollowed and repurposed: a sprawling reconciliation bill locked in upward redistribution and enforcement funding, while purges and layoffs at State, the National Weather Service, FEMA, NASA, and DHS oversight offices weakened neutral capacity and strengthened loyalist control. Against this, there were pockets of resistance\'97courts blocking the birthright\uc0\u8209 citizenship order and a Florida immigration law, legislators pushing transparency, states and civil society suing\'97but they were outweighed by the week\'92s consolidation of power.\
\
The most far\uc0\u8209 reaching development lay in the new legal shelter built around the presidency. The Supreme Court\'92s ruling in Trump v. United States that a former president enjoys \'93absolute immunity\'94 for actions within his \'93conclusive and preclusive\'94 constitutional authority, and \'93presumptive immunity\'94 for all official acts, rewrote the practical meaning of accountability at the top. In one stroke, it raised the cost and uncertainty of any future attempt to prosecute a president for abuses of office, including those that touch elections, war, or foreign affairs. That decision did not stand alone. In the same week, the Court limited nationwide injunctions, making it harder for lower courts to halt executive policies across the country, and it lifted injunctions that had frozen Trump\'92s \'93workforce optimization\'94 order and State Department layoffs. Taken together, these rulings signaled a judiciary increasingly aligned with executive and elite preferences: willing to restrain some state\u8209 level excesses, as in Florida\'92s immigration law, but broadly supportive of a presidency that seeks to act first and litigate later.\
\
This judicial posture mattered because of how the administration chose to use its enlarged space. Trump had already ordered a military strike on Iran without congressional approval, bypassing the war\uc0\u8209 powers framework that is supposed to force shared responsibility for war. He had unilaterally imposed tariffs by declaring a national emergency, turning what should be a legislative domain into a field for presidential decree. An executive order asserted that the Constitution vests foreign policy solely in the president, sidelining Congress\'92s treaty and war powers in theory as well as practice. When the Court then blessed broad immunity for \'93official acts,\'94 it did so in a world where those acts already included unauthorized war, emergency\u8209 based trade policy, and sweeping interventions in law enforcement. The clock moved because the combination of doctrine and behavior made emergency powers feel less like exceptions and more like the normal grammar of governance.\
\
The same pattern appeared in the treatment of law as a flexible instrument rather than a binding limit. Trump pardoned supporters involved in the January 6 attack on the Capitol, sending a clear message that violence in service of his cause would be forgiven. He ordered the Department of Justice to scrutinize and punish political opponents, including by targeting their Secret Service protection, collapsing the line between neutral prosecution and presidential vendetta. The administration instructed DOJ not to enforce a TikTok ban for 75 days while it reviewed the law, asserting the right to decide which statutes would be applied and when. At the same time, DOJ and ICE pursued harsh deportations, including the removal of eight men to South Sudan, most with no ties to that country, after Supreme Court decisions allowed third\uc0\u8209 country deportations. Law was soft and negotiable at the top, hard and unforgiving at the bottom. That asymmetry is what the Democracy Clock measures when it records that \'93law is a weapon, not a limit\'94 as moving sharply upward.\
\
Nowhere was this clearer than in immigration and citizenship. The Department of Homeland Security terminated Temporary Protected Status for roughly 72,000 Hondurans and 4,000 Nicaraguans, ending a quarter\uc0\u8209 century of legal stability and exposing families to removal at executive discretion. ICE detained long\u8209 term residents like Cynthia Olivera, a Canadian mother of three US\u8209 born children, and Arpineh Masihi, who had lived in the country since childhood, during routine processes or in front of their families. A Palestinian activist, Mahmoud Khalil, was held for months as a supposed national security threat without charges, and an imam, Ayman Soliman, saw his asylum revoked over disputed charity ties. These cases were not isolated; they sat alongside a trial challenging an \'93ideological deportation\'94 policy aimed at foreign students with pro\u8209 Palestinian views. Citizenship and legal security were being sorted not only by paperwork, but by nationality, politics, and perceived loyalty. When the administration moved to end birthright citizenship for children of undocumented parents, it crossed from harsh enforcement into an attempt to redraw the constitutional boundary of membership itself.\
\
Here the courts did push back. A federal judge in New Hampshire blocked the birthright\uc0\u8209 citizenship order, certified a nationwide class of affected children, and another judge issued a nationwide block preventing enforcement against babies born after February 20. These rulings, along with the Supreme Court\'92s refusal to let Florida enforce its criminalization of undocumented entry, preserved key elements of the Fourteenth Amendment\'92s promise. They also showed how, after the Court\'92s own limitation on nationwide injunctions, class actions had become the main vehicle for halting sweeping policies. Yet even these victories were defensive and fragile. The same Court that upheld federal primacy over immigration also allowed deportations to third countries and granted immunity to the president. The net effect was a more stratified citizenship regime, in which some protections held while others eroded, and in which the power to decide who belongs tilted further toward the executive.\
\
Beneath these headline fights, the machinery of the state was being remade. The Supreme Court\'92s stays and rulings on Trump\'92s \'93Department of Government Efficiency\'94 order allowed mass layoffs across 19 federal agencies to proceed. The State Department announced plans to cut nearly 15 percent of its domestic staff, then began issuing termination notices to more than 1,300 employees as part of an \'93America First\'94 reorganization. At the National Security Agency and National Security Council, Trump had already fired the NSA director, his deputy, and six NSC staffers after receiving loyalty lists from an outside influencer. The National Security Council itself was described as dysfunctional and blindsided by Pentagon moves. At NASA, Transportation Secretary Sean Duffy was appointed to lead the agency as well, after budget cuts had driven out over 2,000 senior employees. These were not random personnel changes; they were a systematic thinning of expertise and neutral capacity, combined with the elevation of loyalists like Emil Bove to appellate courts and Nick Adams to an ambassadorship. Civil service roles were being made more precarious, more politicized, and more easily reshaped by decree.\
\
The same hollowing appeared in the agencies charged with protecting life and health. The National Weather Service lost more than 600 employees to layoffs and early retirements, leaving storm\uc0\u8209 prone offices understaffed. Congress, with Senator Ted Cruz\'92s help, cut tens of millions from weather\u8209 forecasting research and climate\u8209 impact grants. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and National Science Foundation saw deep budget reductions. In Texas, flash floods killed at least 80 people; officials blamed NWS staffing and funding cuts for inadequate warnings. FEMA, meanwhile, was hamstrung by a new rule from Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem requiring her personal approval for contracts over $100,000. That bottleneck delayed the deployment of Urban Search and Rescue teams for more than 72 hours as the Guadalupe River rose and a girls\'92 camp was swept away. DHS then canceled a $3 million grant meant to improve communication between the Weather Service and local officials, even as search and rescue continued. When the administration announced plans to dismantle FEMA by the end of the hurricane season, arguing that states and private firms could handle disasters, it made explicit what the cuts and delays had already implied: federal emergency management was being treated as dispensable.\
