Public health followed a similar arc. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. dismissed all 17 members of a key CDC vaccine advisory panel, despite earlier pledges not to do so, and replaced them with appointees, many skeptical of vaccines. He spread misinformation on national television, claiming that measles infection was better than vaccination and suggesting that the MMR vaccine caused harms akin to the disease. He launched a large autism research initiative premised on a discredited vaccine link, and he promoted vitamins and cod liver oil as treatments for measles. At the same time, the administration cut funding to health research institutes, and the country recorded at least 1,277 measles cases, a record since the disease had been declared eliminated. Medical organizations, including the American Academy of Pediatrics, sued HHS and Kennedy over these changes, arguing that they violated administrative law and endangered public health. The lawsuits showed that professional bodies still had tools to resist, but the damage to trust and infrastructure was already visible. When science is subordinated to ideology inside the state, the cost is measured in outbreaks and preventable deaths.\
