Immigration enforcement became the most visible theater for the new alignment of law, force, and spectacle. In Los Angeles\'92s MacArthur Park, federal agents, backed by about 90 National Guard troops, rolled in with armored vehicles and tactical gear. One raid, broadcast live by Fox News, lasted an hour and produced no known arrests; Border Patrol\'92s chief later said such operations would become \'93normal.\'94 Another large ICE raid in the same neighborhood prompted a federal judge to issue a temporary restraining order requiring reasonable suspicion for stops and banning racial profiling. In San Francisco, an unmarked ICE SUV drove through a crowd of protesters outside the immigration court, injuring at least one person, while agents without visible badges used rifles, batons, and pepper spray. In southern California, raids on cannabis farms involved chemical munitions against demonstrators and left a farmworker dead. In Florida, a new detention center in the Everglades\'97\'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94\'97opened with reports of maggot\uc0\u8209 infested food, no running water, and exposure to extreme weather. National Guard troops and Marines were deployed to operate detention facilities and assist ICE. At the same time, DHS dismantled its Office for Civil Rights and Civil Liberties and two immigration ombudsman offices, removing internal watchdogs just as arrests and detentions surged.\
