These operations were not only about immigration. They were also about protest and dissent. The deployment of California\'92s National Guard against mostly peaceful protests over immigration raids, over the governor\'92s objections, marked a federal seizure of state military assets to manage domestic opposition. The use of tear gas and armored convoys in urban neighborhoods, the ramming of protesters by an ICE vehicle, and the denial of entry to a member of Congress at a farm raid all signaled that those who opposed the administration\'92s enforcement agenda could expect to meet overwhelming force. Senator Josh Hawley\'92s letter accusing the immigrant\uc0\u8209 rights group Uni\'f3n del Barrio of \'93aiding and abetting criminal conduct\'94 for monitoring ICE patrols framed community defense as criminality. A journalist, Mario Guevara, was arrested while covering protests, handed to ICE, and kept in detention even after local charges were dropped and bond granted. These patterns moved the traits that track protest rights and paramilitary violence: the state was not only tolerating aggressive tactics when they protected elite interests, it was increasingly using them as a first resort.\
