While the domestic field was being reshaped, economic power was wielded outward in ways that blurred policy and personal grievance. Trump announced a 50 percent tariff on Brazilian imports, explicitly tying it to what he called a \'93witch\uc0\u8209 hunt\'94 trial against Jair Bolsonaro for attempting to overturn Brazil\'92s 2022 election. He launched a trade investigation into Brazil\'92s social\u8209 media regulations, denouncing its supreme court\'92s fines on platforms as \'93secret and unlawful censorship orders.\'94 He threatened a 25 percent tariff on all imports from South Korea despite an existing free\u8209 trade agreement, and he rolled out new tariffs on seven other countries, including the Philippines, Libya, and Sri Lanka, with rates between 25 and 30 percent. He imposed a 50 percent tariff on copper, driving US prices to record highs, and announced a 35 percent tariff on Canadian goods. These moves came on top of a 90\u8209 day tariff pause that was repeatedly extended and then reset to August 1, creating whiplash for importers and trade partners. Legally, tariff authority belongs to Congress, with presidents able to act in emergencies; in practice, Trump was using emergency declarations and executive orders to make trade policy, often in service of political fights abroad.\
