Inside the United States, fiscal and regulatory choices deepened the fusion of public power with private gain. The budget reconciliation law made the 2017 tax cuts for the wealthy and corporations permanent, cut $890 billion from Medicaid and $230 billion from SNAP, and allocated $170.7 billion for immigration enforcement, including $51.6 billion for border wall construction and a 265 percent increase in ICE\'92s detention budget. A report from the Quincy Institute and Brown University showed that the new Pentagon budget would push annual military spending past $1 trillion, with more than half of discretionary funds flowing to contractors. USAID cuts were projected to cause over 14 million deaths globally in five years, many among children. At the same time, the IRS filed a document and announced a policy shift allowing churches to endorse political candidates without losing tax\uc0\u8209 exempt status, while other nonprofits remained constrained. This change invited tax\u8209 subsidized religious institutions to act as partisan machines. In Michigan, reporting revealed that DTE Energy and allied interests had used dark money to undermine COVID\u8209 19 public health policies. In education, the White House\'92s AI initiative enlisted 68 technology companies to provide tools, funding, and curricula, while the American Federation of Teachers accepted $23 million from AI firms to create a National Academy for AI Instruction. OpenAI and Google offered free access to their AI tools for students, cultivating future users. In each case, policy and public institutions were being steered toward corporate platforms and contractor revenue, even as social protections were cut.\
