Against this backdrop, there were still acts of institutional resistance and repair. Florida\'92s governor signed a near\uc0\u8209 unanimous bill banning oil drilling near national estuarine reserves, protecting inland waterways from spills. Congress enacted laws restoring municipal lands to Alaska Native villages and clarifying eligibility for Alaska Native settlement trusts, strengthening Indigenous governance and economic self\u8209 determination. California streamlined environmental review for infill housing and advanced manufacturing to address its housing shortage. The Environmental Protection Agency approved multiple state air\u8209 quality plans, corrected lead\u8209 hazard rules, and convened a National Drinking Water Advisory Council meeting on PFAS standards. The Office of Government Information Services scheduled a public FOIA meeting, and the FDA sought comment on identity verification for records requests. Democratic senators introduced a bill to bar ICE agents from wearing masks and to require visible identification, aiming to restore transparency in enforcement. Medical organizations sued HHS over vaccine policy changes, Planned Parenthood challenged Medicaid defunding, and a coalition of 18 states filed an amicus brief against Los Angeles immigration raids. These actions did not reverse the week\'92s damage, but they showed that some levers of law and policy remained in use.\
